{"source_key":"sha256-67ab078c7f660fb9364b7c83113ccb67","record_index":710,"record_hash":"sha256:745a0908f19aee99587857e44643a4de4641ac7437d5f65cfce4d47f7738a884","timestamp":"2026-06-04T15:55:44.531Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_kind":"file_edit","file_path_hashes":["58b6ce960624f3dc9666b1374fd36186"],"tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: posthog-is-gerrit-report.md\n+# PostHog `is_gerrit` Error Bucket Report\n+\n+Generated: 2026-06-04 15:55 UTC\n+\n+## Short version\n+\n+`is_gerrit` is not a release fire, but it is a noisy, user-invisible probe that contributes measurable error telemetry.\n+\n+In `0.20.0`, it contributed:\n+\n+- 119 `query:error` events\n+- 18 affected users\n+- 23 affected sessions\n+- About 2.55% of all `0.20.0` error events\n+- About 0.120 percentage points of the total `0.20.0` error-event rate\n+\n+Fair launch-window comparison:\n+\n+| Version | Error events | Users | Sessions |\n+| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: |\n+| `0.20.0` | 119 | 18 | 23 |\n+| `0.19.13` | 90 | 20 | 22 |\n+\n+So the user count is not worse than the previous release window, but event count is higher. Most of this looks like repeated probing/retries and telemetry capture, not a broad user-facing crash.\n+\n+## What `is_gerrit` Does\n+\n+Frontend endpoint:\n+\n+- `apps/desktop/src/lib/project/projectEndpoints.ts`\n+- Endpoint name: `areYouGerritKiddingMe`\n+- Telemetry command: `is_gerrit`\n+\n+Frontend caller:\n+\n+- `apps/desktop/src/components/onboarding/ProjectSetupTarget.svelte`\n+- Used during project setup to decide whether to show the \"Enable Gerrit project\" prompt.\n+- The component explicitly renders an empty error state: \"Fail silently to detect the gerritness of a project\".\n+\n+Backend endpoint:\n+\n+- `crates/but-api/src/legacy/projects.rs`\n+- `is_gerrit(ctx)` calls `gitbutler_project::gerrit::is_used_by_default_remote(&*ctx.repo.get()?)`.\n+\n+Actual probe:\n+\n+- `crates/gitbutler-project/src/gerrit.rs`\n+- Checks the default push remote.\n+- Replaces fetch refspecs with `refs/meta/config`.\n+- Connects to the remote with `Direction::Push`.\n+- Calls `ref_map(...)`.\n+- Returns `true` if remote refs are non-empty.\n+\n+The important bit: this is a network/remote probe, and it can trigger credential, URL, SSH, HTTP, and remote capability failures just to decide whether to show an optional Gerrit prompt.\n+\n+## Telemetry Caveat\n+\n+The UI intends the Gerrit detection failure to be silent, but the shared query hook still emits `query:error`.\n+\n+Relevant code:\n+\n+- `apps/desktop/src/lib/state/customHooks.svelte`\n+- Query errors call `emitQueryError(posthog, error, { command, actionName })`.\n+- `apps/desktop/src/lib/error/error.ts` emits `query:error`.\n+- There is rate limiting per key, but the bucket still accumulates.\n+\n+This means `is_gerrit` can pollute release-health telemetry even when the user sees no failure UI.\n+\n+## Error Shape In `0.20.0`\n+\n+All current `0.20.0` `is_gerrit` events are `query:error`.\n+\n+Top buckets:\n+\n+| Error class | Events | Users | OS |\n+| --- | ---: | ---: | --- |\n+| Failed to obtain username credentials; terminal prompt failed with `Device not configured` | 49 | 8 | macOS |\n+| No push remotes found | 33 | 2 | Linux, Windows |\n+| Smart protocol header missing; dumb protocol unsupported | 10 | 2 | Windows |\n+| SSH credentials rejected / publickey denied | 8 | 1 | Windows |\n+| Failed to obtain password credentials; terminal prompt failed | 5 | 1 | macOS |\n+| Invalid SSH URL passed for transport configuration | 5 | 1 | Linux |\n+| GitHub SSH publickey denied | 3 | 1 | Linux |\n+| Refused to send credentials over clear-text HTTP | 3 | 1 | Windows |\n+| Could not resolve SSH hostname | 3 | 1 | Windows |\n+\n+Common pattern: the Gerrit detector touches remotes that are private, missing, invalid, HTTP-only, SSH-only, or need credentials. Those failures are mostly normal remote-access conditions, not necessarily app regressions.\n+\n+## Comparison With `0.19.13`\n+\n+The same classes existed in `0.19.13`.\n+\n+Notable previous-version buckets:\n+\n+- Failed to obtain username credentials: [REDACTED:entropy] events, 87 users\n+- Clear-text HTTP credential refusal: 194 events, 15 users\n+- Network IO errors: 43 events, 14 users\n+- Linux terminal prompt failure: 29 events, 9 users\n+- No push remotes found: 13 events, 4 users\n+\n+So this is not a brand-new failure mode. `0.20.0` does have a slightly higher event count in the matched launch window, but fewer affected users.\n+\n+## Why It Matters\n+\n+It probably does not break the main app flow because the onboarding UI intentionally hides this probe failure.\n+\n+But it does matter because:\n+\n+- It contributes to release error-event rate.\n+- It may perform unnecessary network/auth work during setup.\n+- It can ask lower-level git/transport code to obtain credentials even though this is only optional Gerrit detection.\n+- It may generate repeated telemetry from a non-actionable probe.\n+\n+## Likely Root Cause\n+\n+The detector is too eager and too invasive.\n+\n+It tries to prove Gerrit support by connecting to the default push remote and requesting `refs/meta/config`. That makes sense as a strong signal, but it is overkill for a UI hint. On many private repositories, this requires credentials or fails noisily.\n+\n+For a \"does this smell like Gerrit?\" prompt, network failures should probably be treated as \"unknown / false\", not telemetry-worthy errors.\n+\n+## Suggested Fix Directions\n+\n+Pick one:\n+\n+1. Best quick fix: make `areYouGerritKiddingMe` suppress telemetry errors.\n+   - Add an option to query hooks or endpoint metadata to avoid `emitQueryError`.\n+   - Use it for this endpoint because the UI already treats failure as silent.\n+\n+2. Better product fix: make `is_gerrit` return `false` or `Unknown` for non-actionable probe failures.\n+   - `No push remotes found`\n+   - credential prompt unavailable\n+   - credentials rejected\n+   - clear-text HTTP credential refusal\n+   - invalid remote URL\n+   - DNS/SSH/network failures\n+   - smart/dumb protocol mismatch\n+\n+3. Better architecture fix: avoid live network auth probes for onboarding hints.\n+   - Prefer cheap remote URL/config heuristics.\n+   - Only do the expensive probe after the user opts into Gerrit mode, or behind an explicit \"check\" action.\n+\n+My preference: do option 1 immediately to clean release telemetry, then option 3 if Gerrit detection continues to matter.\n+\n+## Investigation Pointers\n+\n+Start here:\n+\n+- `apps/desktop/src/components/onboarding/ProjectSetupTarget.svelte`\n+- `apps/desktop/src/lib/project/projectEndpoints.ts`\n+- `apps/desktop/src/lib/state/customHooks.svelte`\n+- `apps/desktop/src/lib/error/error.ts`\n+- `crates/but-api/src/legacy/projects.rs`\n+- `crates/gitbutler-project/src/gerrit.rs`\n+\n+Questions for the fixing agent:\n+\n+- Should the endpoint return `Result<Option<bool>>` or a richer `GerritDetection` enum?\n+- Should query endpoints support `suppressTelemetryOnError`?\n+- Is a remote network probe acceptable during onboarding render?\n+- Can `gix` be configured for this probe to never prompt for credentials?\n+- Are we okay treating \"remote requires auth\" as \"not detected\" for the purposes of a UI hint?\n+\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-04T15:55:44.531Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}